  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Maximum sentences can increase based on specific circumstances\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial fines, potentially up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved\n- Forfeiture of assets related to the laundering activity\n\n3. Additional potential consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Asset seizure\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Immigration consequences for non-citizens\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors like:\n- Amount of money involved\n- Specific federal statute violated\n- Whether the offense is related to other criminal activities\n- Individual's prior criminal history\n\nProsecution typically occurs through statutes like:\n- Bank Secrecy Act\n- Money Laundering Control Act\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\nThese penalties are designed to deter financial crimes and protect the integrity of financial systems.\n\nNote: This is general legal information, not specific legal advice. Actual penalties can vary based on individual case details.",
